# What is Machine Learning?
*Understanding the fundamental concepts*

---

# Traditional Programming vs ML

<<mermaid>>
graph LR
    subgraph "Traditional Programming"
        A[Input Data] --> B[Program]
        B --> C[Output]
    end
    
    subgraph "Machine Learning"
        D[Input Data] --> E[ML Algorithm]
        F[Expected Output] --> E
        E --> G[Program/Model]
    end
    
    style B fill:#E74C3C,color:#fff
    style E fill:#27AE60,color:#fff
    style G fill:#3498DB,color:#fff
<</mermaid>>

**Key difference**: ML learns patterns from data instead of explicit programming

---

# Types of Machine Learning

::: info
**Supervised Learning**
- Learn from labeled examples
- Predict outcomes for new data
- Examples: Email spam detection, image recognition
:::

::: warning
**Unsupervised Learning**
- Find patterns in unlabeled data
- Discover hidden structures
- Examples: Customer segmentation, anomaly detection
:::

::: tip
**Reinforcement Learning**
- Learn through interaction and feedback
- Optimize decisions over time
- Examples: Game playing, robotics, autonomous vehicles
:::

---

# The ML Workflow

<<mermaid>>
graph TD
    A[Problem Definition] --> B[Data Collection]
    B --> C[Data Preprocessing]
    C --> D[Feature Engineering]
    D --> E[Model Selection]
    E --> F[Training]
    F --> G[Evaluation]
    G --> H{Performance OK?}
    H -->|No| D
    H -->|Yes| I[Deployment]
    I --> J[Monitoring]
    J --> K{Drift Detected?}
    K -->|Yes| B
    K -->|No| J
    
    style A fill:#3498DB,color:#fff
    style F fill:#E74C3C,color:#fff
    style I fill:#27AE60,color:#fff
<</mermaid>>

**Iterative process**: Continuous improvement through feedback loops

